      <hedline>
        <hl1>Feasts Are for All Senses</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Josephine Colmenares letter disputes July 26 letter responding to article on wine reviewers, which stated that people are interested mostly in taste, but not smell</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I disagree with the reader who wrote that people are ''all interested in taste, not smell,'' in response to the article on wine reviewers who discard wines after smelling but not tasting them (Letters, July 26).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I disagree with the reader who wrote that people are ''all interested in taste, not smell,'' in response to the article on wine reviewers who discard wines after smelling but not tasting them (Letters, July 26).</p>
        <p>Eating is one activity that engages all five senses. I may pass on a dish that is not visually appealing (I once had a difficult time eating a wonderful octopus salad because I did not like how it looked) or I may abandon a dish after one taste if I don't care for its texture. And with the possible exception of parmigiano, I will not eat anything that smells bad.</p>
        <p>JOSEPHINE  COLMENARES  Brooklyn</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
